Introduction¶

This documentation explores a diabetes dataset of females at least 21 years and older. Females are of Pima Indian Heritage. There are 768 observation with 9 variables in the dataset. Dataset can be found here.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 768 females in the dataset with 9 features (Pregnancies, Glucose, BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, Age, and Outcome). All features are numeric except Outcome which is a categorical variable where 0 means no diabetes and 1 meaning diabetes.

Pregnancies: Number of times a woman was pregnant.

Glucose: Plasma glucoes concentration after 2 hours on an oral glucose tolerance test (no unit was specified).

Blood pressure: Diastolic blood pressure measured in mmHg.

SkinThickness: Triceps skin fold thickness measured in mm.

Insulin: Serum insulin after 2 hours measured in mu U/ml.

BMI: Body mass index measured in kg/m^2.

DiabetesPedigreeFunction: Diabetes pedigree function which is a function that score the likelihood of having diabetes based on the family history of the participant.

Age: Age of participant in years.

Outcome: Represented whether participant had diabetes (0: No, 1: Yes).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in examining the relationship between the features (Pregnancies, Glucose, BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, Age) and Outcome.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I hypothesize that features such as Number of pregnancies, Glucose, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI, DiabetesPedigreeFunction and Age will be strongly associated with the outcome of diabetes.

Univariate Exploration¶

In [12]:
# Histogram function

def histogram(x):
    plt.hist(x, bins = np.arange(0, x.max()+5,5))
    
# Function to create histogram distributions, log transformations and box plot

def histogram_distributions(x):
    ## Figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=[30,5])

    ## Subplot 1 
    plt.subplot(1,4,1)
    histogram(x)


    ## Subplot 2 
    plt.subplot(1,4,2)
    sns.distplot(x);


    ## Subplot 3
    plt.subplot(1,4,3)
    sns.distplot(x);
    plt.xscale("log")
    
    ## Subplot 4
    plt.subplot(1,4,4)
    x.plot(kind="box");

Q1. What is the distribution of pregnancies among study participants?¶

In [13]:

## Distribution of pregnancies
plt.hist(diabetes["Pregnancies"]);

histogram_distributions(diabetes["Pregnancies"]);

Observation: The distribution of pregnancies is skewed to the right with majority of women having 1-5 pregnancies and a few having above 15 pregnancies. Log transformation in the second distribution plot did not deal with the skewness of the variable. The boxplot depicts outliers with the number of pregnancies. The outliers also contribute to the observed skewness in the feature.

Q2: What is the distribution of plasma glucose concentration among study participants 2 hours after an oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT)?¶

In [14]:
# Univariate exploration of Glucose
histogram_distributions(diabetes["Glucose"])

Observation: The distribution of glucose concentration is skewed to the right. Outliers in blood glucose concentration are below 50 with majority of readings between 75 and 150. Adding a log transformation has minimised the skewness and makes the distribution appear normal. In contrast to earlier observation made from the distribution plot, the boxplot distribution does not indicate the presence of an outlier in the distribution of plasma glucose concentration.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Number of pregnancies, triceps skinfold thickness, insulin, BMI, diabetes pedigree funtion and age were skewed to to the right. All variables stated were transformed using the log transfomation scale. However, number of pregnancies did not appear normally distribution after applying log transformation. Outliers were remove and the distribution appeared to be normally distributed. The distribution of glucose appeared normally distributed with no outliers present. Blood pressure measurement had outliers on both sides of the distribution and as such, distribution was not clearly skewed in any direction. Outliers present in the features were removed to minimise skewness. Outliers also tend to introduce bias and influence the results of hypothesis testing.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Diabetes is associated with age, number of pregnancies, blood pressure, triceps skinfold thickness, serum insulin measurement, BMI, and Diabetes Pedigree Function. Participants with diabetes were older compared to participants without diabetes. Participants with diabetes had higher values for number of pregnancies, blood pressure, triceps skinfold, serum insulin measurement, serum glucose, BMI and Diabetes pedigree function on average compared to participants without diabetes.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

BMI and Triceps skinfold thickness had a strong correlation as well as the serum glucose and insulin.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [39]:
# Scatter plot matrix
sns.pairplot(diabetes, dropna = True, hue = "Outcome");

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Participants with diabetes clearly had higher serum glucose levels and insulin levels. As expected, when serum glucose increases which may lead to a diagnosis of diabetes, endogenous insulin production also tend to increase.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Participants with higher BMI and higher triceps skinfold had some participants with and without diabetes. The relationship between triceps skinfold and BMI stratified by diabetes is not clear enough to warrant the significant association between diabetes, BMI and triceps skinfold.

Conclusions¶

Univariate exploration was used to create visualisation for single features to investigate distributions as well as frequency counts. Bivariate exploration was used to create visualisation to investigation the relationship between two features. Then, multivariate exploration was used to explore the relation between more than two features. All in all, diabetes as an outcome of interest was associated with age, number of pregnancies, blood pressure, triceps skinfold thickness, serum insulin measurement, BMI, and Diabetes Pedigree Function. Participants with diabetes were on average older than participants without diabetes. The chances of diabetes increased with increasing number of pregnancies, blood pressure, triceps skinfold thinckness and BMI. Participants with diabetes had higher amounts of serum insulin compared to participants without diabetes and a higher Diabetes Pedigree Funtion on average was also associated with increased chances of having diabetes.
